\section*{\centerline{Abstract}}

Most of the widely used methods of modeling outcomes of infectious disease outbreaks begin with a generalized linear model (GLM) of disease incidence, followed by estimation of the outcome measure of interest from incidence estimates. Calculation of outcome measures of clinical and public health significance is typically non-trivial, and consequently only point estimates (rather than interval estimates) of those measures can be made from the model. In our ongoing work on respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) seasonality, we developed a general method for obtaining interval estimates of outcome measures of seasonal and sporadic infectious disease outbreaks using multivariate sampling of a generalized additive model (GAM) with penalized basis splines (P-splines). Our approach provides robust interval estimates regardless of the complexity of the calculations of the outcome measures, and it generalizes to other systems (including outbreaks of other infectious diseases). Here we present our general approach, its application to RSV, and an R package that provides a convenient interface for conducting and validating this type of analysis in other areas.

