\section{Introduction}

A typical mathematical model of an infectious disease --- either during an outbreak, or during a stable period of disease --- treats observed disease incidence as the outcome variable in a generalized linear model (GLM) or a generalized additive model (GAM). This broad framework encompasses a variety of advanced modeling methods such as Fourier analysis of disease periodicity and changepoint analysis of impact of preventative measures. 

At the outset of analysis based on this framework, model terms are chosen to represent predictors of disease incidence; at the conclusion of analysis, the model produces estimates of model parameters. Depending on the details of the model, model parameter estimates may be point estimates or interval estimates. For example, Fourier analysis of periodicity produces point estimates of seasonal amplitude. 

Many questions of interest in clinical and public health practice are not directly answered by model parameter estimation. For example, while Fourier analysis can estimate the amplitude of a seasonal outbreak and the time interval between consecutive seasonal outbreaks, it does not directly answer more complex questions such as ``What fraction of cases occur after the outbreak has peaked?'' or ``How much time passes between the 100th recorded case of the disease and the outbreak peak?''. Both of those questions can --- in principle --- be answered from periodicity analysis, provided that one develops the necessary ad-hoc methods, and even then the best one could hope for with the approaches commonly in use today would be a point estimate, not an interval estimate.

We encountered this limitation in our respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) research, in which we wanted to estimate three measures of a seasonal outbreak: the time it began (onset), the time it ended (offset), and the fraction of cases that occurred while a specific prophylaxis regimen was in effect (protected fraction). (Ref main paper) To address this, we devised a method that allows interval estimation of any outcome measure computable from estimates of disease incidence. In brief, our approach begins by fitting observed RSV incidence to penalized splines (P-splines), which are smoothing curves with several qualities desirable in analysis of experimental data --- including computational compactness and efficiency, and well-understood statistical behavior. \cite{Eilers:1996kz} As we will describe in detail below, we then sample estimates of disease incidence from the P-spline model, and finally sample the outcome measure of interest (for example, season onset) from those estimates of disease incidence. By repeating this process, we are able to infer the distribution of the outcome measures of interest and thereby make interval estimates.

\section{Methods}

\subsection{Background}

\subsubsection{Generalized additive modeling}

A \textit{generalized additive model} (GAM --- sometimes known as a generalized linear model, GLM) provides a means of estimating a response variable $y$, using multiple predictor variables $x_i$ with associated smooth predictor functions $f_i$ and a function $g$ (\textit{link function}) such that:

\begin{equation*}
    g(\hat{y}) = \beta_0 + f_1(x_1) + f_2(x_2) + \dots + f_n(x_n)
\end{equation*}

\subsubsection{Basis splines}

A \textit{spline} of order $n$ is a piecewise polynomial function of degree $n - 1$ on $[t_a, t_b] \subset \mathds{R}$; the points at which its polynomial segments join are known as \textit{knots} $k_i$. Owing to its construction, a spline of order $n$ has up to  $n - 1$ continuous derivatives throughout $[t_a, t_b]$; for our analysis, we only consider splines with exactly $n - 1$ continuous derivatives.

Given a set of knots $k_i$, we can construct a unique set of splines of order $n$ (with those knots) known as the \textit{basis splines} (B-splines) and denoted with $B_i$. All other splines with knots $k_i$ can be represented as a linear combination of the basis splines with knots $k_i$.

\subsubsection{Cyclic splines}

A \textit{cyclic spline} of order $n$ is a piecewise polynomial periodic function $f(x) = f(x - T)$ on $\mathds{R}$. A cyclic spline of order $n$ is continuous in up to $n - 1$ derivatives, and we only consider cyclic splines continuous in exactly $n - 1$ derivatives. Use of cyclic splines is often necessary in infectious disease modeling because non-cyclic splines do not guarantee smoothness at $t_a \pm k T$ when extended to $\mathds{R}$.

\subsubsection{Penalized B-splines in GAM}

Splines, by virtue of their smoothness, can be used as predictor functions $f_i$ in a GAM. Expressed in terms of B-splines, $f_i =  \sum_j \beta_{i,j} B_{i,j}$, and the GAM takes the form:

\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
    g(\hat{y}) &= \beta_0 \\
    &+ \beta_{1,1} B_{1,1}(x_1) + \beta_{1,2} B_{1,2}(x_1) + \dots \\
    &+ \beta_{2,1} B_{2,1}(x_2) + \beta_{2,2} B_{2,2}(x_2) + \dots \\
    &+ \dots \\
    &+ \beta_{n,1} B_{n,1}(x_n) + \beta_{n,2} B_{n,2}(x_n) + \dots
\end{aligned}\label{eqn:model}
\end{equation}

This model can be fitted to data simply by minimizing $\Vert y - \hat{y} \Vert^2$; however, this approach often leads to overfitting, especially with a larger number of knots. To mitigate this, the model can be modified to instead minimize $\Vert y - \hat{y} \Vert^2 + P$, where $P$ is a \textit{penalty function} that measures non-smoothness of the model. This approach balances closeness of fit with smoothness. B-splines used in a model with a penalty function are known as \textit{penalized B-splines} (P-splines). A variety of penalty functions have been defined; the most common ones use $k$-th order differences between the model and the data, for some small integer $k$ (often $k = 2$). As with general cyclic splines, \textit{cyclic P-splines} are an extension of P-splines to periodic functions.

For smooth estimation of non-linear experimental data, P-splines have desirable computational and statistical properties. Most notably for our application, P-spline parameters $\beta_{i,j}$ estimated by GAM are normally distributed (provided that the underlying phenomenon is well-approximated by a piecewise-polynomial function). 

\subsection{Outcome estimation}

The principal questions of our RSV work were:

\begin{itemize}
\item Is the period during which RSV prophylaxis is administered well-matched to the timing of RSV seasons?
\item Could the prophylaxis period be adjusted so that more of the preventable RSV cases occur during the prophylaxis period?
\end{itemize}

To that end, we defined the following outcome measures of interest:

\begin{itemize}
\item Season onset and offset, defined as the points in time when the cumulative incidence of RSV rises above 2.5\% and 97.5\% of the total incidence of RSV for the entire season
\item Preventable fraction of a prophylaxis regimen, defined as the fraction of all RSV cases occurring during the period when the prophylaxis regimen provides protection from RSV. 
\end{itemize}

Once we constructed a P-spline GAM (Equation \ref{eqn:model}) and fit it to our incidence data, we could sample the model parameters $\beta_{i,j}$, use them to estimate the  model response variable (in our case, RSV incidence), and therefrom estimate the outcome measures of interest. By way of example, consider the (hypothetical) RSV season shown in Figure \ref{fig:sampleCases}. 

