\section{Results}

Our simulation study found that the true value of season onset was included in the estimated $95$\% confidence interval in $\Sexpr{round(100*validationResults$summary$onset.good, 2)}$\% of the simulations. The distribution of the true season onset's percentile in each simulation's distribution of season onset estimates is shown in Figure \ref{fig:simPctileOnset}.

We similarly found that the true value of season offset was included in the estimated $95$\% confidence interval in $\Sexpr{round(100*validationResults$summary$offset.good, 2)}$\% of the simulations. The distribution of the true season offset's percentile in each simulation's distribution of season offset estimates is shown in Figure \ref{fig:simPctileOffset}.

Finally, we found that the true value of the protected fraction was included TODO %in the estimated $95$\% confidence interval in $\Sexpr{round(100*validationResults$summary$offset.good, 2)}$\% of the simulations. The distribution of the true season offset's percentile in each simulation's distribution of season offset estimates is shown in Figure \ref{fig:simPctileOffset}.

In summary, our simulation study validated our method of interval estimation for all three outcome measures of interest in our RSV research.

\section{Discussion}

We chose the specific outcome measures (onset/offset time and protected fraction) to serve our RSV research; validating our estimation of those outcomes gives methodological grounding to our RSV results, as well as opening up the possibility of applying them to investigations of other infectious  disease outbreaks. In particular, we plan to investigate the potential benefits of regional RSV prophylaxis guidelines by applying our methods to RSV in states other than Connecticut. 

That said, the greater significance of our results rests neither specifically with RSV nor specifically with those outcome measures. The R package we wrote to encapsulate our methods in an easy-to-use programming interface --- \texttt{pspline.inference} --- allows the user to obtain interval estimates of an arbitrary user-defined outcome measure (as long as it's computable from the model response variable), regardless of how complex its computation; it also provides an easy way to conduct a simulation study to validate estimation of the user-defined outcome measure on user-supplied data, thereby making it simple to develop and validate novel outcome measures. The package is available on GitHub and (TODO) CRAN, and its documentation includes examples beyond those shown here.

